Music described as '''piano six hands''' (or piano trio).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colstonhall.org/shows/piano-triets|title=Piano Triets / Shows / Colston Hall|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://seenandheard-international.com/2012/04/piano-music-for-six-hands-the-shape-of-the-future|title=Piano Music for Six Hands; The Shape of the Future? : Seen and Heard International|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://www.laurashur.co.uk/lauracompos.htm</ref> is for three pianists at one piano, as distinct from [[piano duet]] which is music for two [[pianist]]s at one or two pianos. Because of the limited range available to each player, many of the pieces written for this combination are elementary in nature; many more are arrangements of pieces for other forces. But there are a small number of original works, and a handful of virtuoso three-player groups have emerged in the 21st century.
==Examples== Compositions include five pieces by [[Percy Grainger]], [[Sergei Rachmaninoff]]'s Romance and Valse, [[Alfred Schnittke]]'s Hommage, [[Carl Czerny]]'s opp. 17, 84, 227-229, 295-298, 609, 689, 741 and 798, [[Jean Cras]]'s "Âmes d’enfants", [[Paul Robinson (composer)|Paul Robinson]]'s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://paulrobinsoncomposer.com/compositions.html|title=Compositions|website=paulrobinsoncomposer.com}}</ref> "Pensees" and "Montmartre", various pieces by German composer {{ill|Armin Fuchs|de}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armin-fuchs.com/komponist/kompositionen/index.html|title=Kompositionen|first=Armin|last=Fuchs|website=www.armin-fuchs.com}}</ref> Bulgarian composer [[Tomislav Baynov]]'s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baynov-piano.de|title=baynov-piano.de|website=www.baynov-piano.de}}</ref> "Metrorhythmia 1",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eTPGHFDaPcA|title=three girls and one piano- Some Handsome Hands|first=|last=Anne Salié|date=18 March 2007|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eV7Iu7sN_Kc|title=Tomislav Baynov Metrorhythmia 1 for Piano Six Hands|first=|last=veseli601|date=16 July 2009|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> [[John Pitts (composer)|John Pitts]]'s "Are You Going?",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/tw.asp?w=W14945|title=Are you going? for piano triet - Hyperion Records - CDs, MP3 and Lossless downloads|website=www.hyperion-records.co.uk}}</ref> Greek composer [[Dionysis Boukouvalas]]'s "Fantasy on a theme by Steve Reich", Canadian composer [[Paul Frehner]]'s "Slowdown"<ref>http://www.musiccentre.ca/media/bioattachments/en/frehn%20_61861_compositions.pdf</ref>, Malaysian composer [[Samuel Cho]]'s "S[wim]"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.samuelchomusic.com/works/chamber/swim/|title=S[wim] (2016) for three pianists, one piano|website=SAMUEL CHO|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-04}}</ref>.
